      },
      "body": "I understand that bip 159 uses the word \"pruning\" and that it can be used as an alias for \"limited\", but internally in Bitcoin Core, pruning usually means that blocks are deleted. However, a limited peer may be limited for other reasons, for example:\r\n\r\n* AU-background download is still in progress (possible today in Bitcoin Core)\r\n* A node that just wants to limit itself (similar to maxuploadtarget?)\r\n* ...\r\n\r\nSo I think it would be better to not imply the two words mean the same here.",
